english:
  title: Record of a Journey to the Northern Cliff of Gwanaksa Temple
  author: Seong Gan
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the sixth month of summer, I sought refuge from the heat at Gwanaksa Temple. Day after day, I wandered with the monks through the mountain's deep forests and strange stone formations, convinced that I had seen all the wonders this mountain had to offer. One day I said to them, "I have grown weary of landscapes. Yet the northern reaches of this mountain—I have marked them as singular, but never explored them. Will you not guide me there?" They replied, "The forest to the north runs deeper still, the stones rise more sheer, the path is blocked. We cannot reach the end." But I urged them on.

    We cut through the tangled growth and began our ascent from the western slope, pushing through bramble and thistle, curving northward as the mountain's face grew ever more precipitous. Climbing by vine and root, when exhaustion overtook us, we grasped the hanging kudzu to rest. At last we reached the summit.

    There stood a cliff like a great hall, curving around us, its depths plunging nearly a thousand feet below. At first my spirit trembled with awe. Then I stretched my legs and sat firmly upon that stone. Soon the wind came—a whisper of pine needles carrying across ten thousand valleys—and the oppressive heat withdrew. Below, fish and birds moved through water, and all the verdant growth of grass and wood flourished before my eyes. Turning west, I gazed where the sea met heaven, mist and cloud hanging thick and dim. As the sun descended toward the waves, its light shot forth in scattered rays—red as crimson, blue as azure, black as night, white as snow—a spectacle as if spirits themselves were gathering.

    Alas, how many scholars have wandered this mountain? How many monks? Yet none have spoken of this cliff. By fortune, my journey revealed it to me. Can it be that the Creator prepared this place for me alone? Zhuangzi once said, "Great forests and high mountains bring benefit to people, yet their sublime mystery surpasses mortal capacity." Yet Zhuangzi may not have understood his own words truly.

    When a person dwells in this world, ten thousand affairs press from without, and a hundred anxieties stir within, until the breath grows stifled and the spirit grows sluggish. But when one encounters mountains vast and sublime, valleys fair and enchanting—when uprightness strikes the eye and clarity strikes the ear—then all that old oppression and blockage dissolves without trace. Those ancients who found aid in mountains and waters: how could Zhuangzi's words suffice to explain them?

    Recorded on the sixteenth day of this month.
  footnotes:
    - Zhuangzi (莊周) refers to the famous Daoist philosopher and author of the Zhuangzi text, known for his paradoxical wisdom about nature and human limitation.
    - The 'Northern Cliff' (北巖) represents a place of transcendence where the author experiences both physical exertion and spiritual renewal, a common theme in East Asian landscape writing.
